TY  - JOUR
T1  - Recent Trends in US Income Distributions in Tax Record Data Using More Comprehensive Measures of Income Including Real Accrued Capital Gains
AU  - Larrimore, Jeff
AU  - Burkhauser, Richard V.
AU  - Auten, Gerald
AU  - Armour, Philip
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713098
DO  - 10.1086/713098
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1319
EP  - 1360
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Use of Internal Revenue Service (IRS) tax records improves researchers? ability to track income trends, although the focus on taxable market income in this research excludes important income sources. Using IRS data in combination with other data sources, we explore the effect of measuring inequality levels and trends with income, including real accrued capital gains based on Haig-Simons principles. While median market income fell 10% from 1989 to 2016, median economic income increased by 26% using our Haig-Simons-based measure. Top 1% income shares were lower and increased by only about one-third of that estimated using previous approaches over this period.
AB  - Use of Internal Revenue Service (IRS) tax records improves researchers? ability to track income trends, although the focus on taxable market income in this research excludes important income sources. Using IRS data in combination with other data sources, we explore the effect of measuring inequality levels and trends with income, including real accrued capital gains based on Haig-Simons principles. While median market income fell 10% from 1989 to 2016, median economic income increased by 26% using our Haig-Simons-based measure. Top 1% income shares were lower and increased by only about one-third of that estimated using previous approaches over this period.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713098
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713098
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Human Capital Investments and Expectations about Career and Family
AU  - Wiswall, Matthew
AU  - Zafar, Basit
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713100
DO  - 10.1086/713100
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1361
EP  - 1424
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We conducted a survey of high-ability college students and elicited beliefs about how their choice of major, and of whether to complete their degree, would affect an array of future events: earnings, employment, marriage prospects, potential spousal characteristics, and fertility. We find that students perceive large ?returns? to human capital not only in their own future earnings but also in other dimensions (e.g., potential spouse?s earnings and fertility). We find evidence of students sorting into majors on the basis of these perceived returns. Family expectations are particularly important for female students? major choices. In a follow-up survey conducted 6 years after the initial data collection, we find a close connection between expectations and current realizations.
AB  - We conducted a survey of high-ability college students and elicited beliefs about how their choice of major, and of whether to complete their degree, would affect an array of future events: earnings, employment, marriage prospects, potential spousal characteristics, and fertility. We find that students perceive large ?returns? to human capital not only in their own future earnings but also in other dimensions (e.g., potential spouse?s earnings and fertility). We find evidence of students sorting into majors on the basis of these perceived returns. Family expectations are particularly important for female students? major choices. In a follow-up survey conducted 6 years after the initial data collection, we find a close connection between expectations and current realizations.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713100
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713100
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - How to Improve Tax Compliance? Evidence from Population-Wide Experiments in Belgium
AU  - De Neve, Jan-Emmanuel
AU  - Imbert, Clément
AU  - Spinnewijn, Johannes
AU  - Tsankova, Teodora
AU  - Luts, Maarten
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713096
DO  - 10.1086/713096
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1425
EP  - 1463
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We study the impact of simplification, deterrence, and tax morale on tax compliance. We ran four natural field experiments varying the communication of the tax administration with the universe of income taxpayers in Belgium throughout the tax process. A consistent picture emerges across experiments: (i) simplifying communication substantially increases compliance, (ii) deterrence messages have an additional positive effect, (iii) invoking tax morale is not effective and often backfires. A discontinuity in enforcement intensity, combined with the experimental variation, allows us to compare simplification with standard enforcement measures. We find that simplification is far more cost-effective, allowing for substantial savings on enforcement costs.
AB  - We study the impact of simplification, deterrence, and tax morale on tax compliance. We ran four natural field experiments varying the communication of the tax administration with the universe of income taxpayers in Belgium throughout the tax process. A consistent picture emerges across experiments: (i) simplifying communication substantially increases compliance, (ii) deterrence messages have an additional positive effect, (iii) invoking tax morale is not effective and often backfires. A discontinuity in enforcement intensity, combined with the experimental variation, allows us to compare simplification with standard enforcement measures. We find that simplification is far more cost-effective, allowing for substantial savings on enforcement costs.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713096
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713096
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - An Investment-and-Marriage Model with Differential Fecundity: On the College Gender Gap
AU  - Zhang, Hanzhe
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713097
DO  - 10.1086/713097
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1464
EP  - 1486
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - I build an investment-and-marriage model to provide a new explanation for the reversed college gender gap; that is, more women than men are going to college. The explanation is based on differential fecundity and an equilibrium marriage-market effect. The model also sheds light on gender-specific relationships between age at marriage and midlife personal income for American men and women and the evolving relationship between age at marriage and spousal income for American women.
AB  - I build an investment-and-marriage model to provide a new explanation for the reversed college gender gap; that is, more women than men are going to college. The explanation is based on differential fecundity and an equilibrium marriage-market effect. The model also sheds light on gender-specific relationships between age at marriage and midlife personal income for American men and women and the evolving relationship between age at marriage and spousal income for American women.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713097
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713097
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Search, Liquidity, and Retention: Screening Multidimensional Private Information
AU  - Williams, Basil
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713099
DO  - 10.1086/713099
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1487
EP  - 1507
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - A large literature has shown that asset quality may be signaled by retention or, in a separate literature, screened by liquidity. I present a general framework to analyze both instruments, offering conditions that characterize which instrument will be used in equilibrium. I then expand the private information to include not only asset quality but also seller patience, showing that both retention and liquidity may be used to fully separate both dimensions of private information. The expanded model offers new predictions about how price, quantity, and liquidity covary with each other and with seller private information.
AB  - A large literature has shown that asset quality may be signaled by retention or, in a separate literature, screened by liquidity. I present a general framework to analyze both instruments, offering conditions that characterize which instrument will be used in equilibrium. I then expand the private information to include not only asset quality but also seller patience, showing that both retention and liquidity may be used to fully separate both dimensions of private information. The expanded model offers new predictions about how price, quantity, and liquidity covary with each other and with seller private information.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713099
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713099
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - East-Side Story: Historical Pollution and Persistent Neighborhood Sorting
AU  - Heblich, Stephan
AU  - Trew, Alex
AU  - Zylberberg, Yanos
Y1  - 2020/12/18
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713101
DO  - 10.1086/713101
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1508
EP  - 1552
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Why are the east sides of formerly industrial cities more deprived? To answer this question, we use individual-level census data and create historical pollution patterns derived from the locations of 5,000 industrial chimneys and an atmospheric model. We show that this observation results from path-dependent neighborhood sorting that began during the Industrial Revolution, as prevailing winds blew pollution eastward. Past pollution explains up to 20% of observed neighborhood segregation in 2011, even though coal pollution stopped in the 1970s. We develop a quantitative model to identify the role of neighborhood effects and relocation rigidities underlying this persistence.
AB  - Why are the east sides of formerly industrial cities more deprived? To answer this question, we use individual-level census data and create historical pollution patterns derived from the locations of 5,000 industrial chimneys and an atmospheric model. We show that this observation results from path-dependent neighborhood sorting that began during the Industrial Revolution, as prevailing winds blew pollution eastward. Past pollution explains up to 20% of observed neighborhood segregation in 2011, even though coal pollution stopped in the 1970s. We develop a quantitative model to identify the role of neighborhood effects and relocation rigidities underlying this persistence.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713101
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713101
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Impure Impact Giving: Theory and Evidence
AU  - Hungerman, Daniel M.
AU  - Ottoni-Wilhelm, Mark
Y1  - 2020/12/23
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713190
DO  - 10.1086/713190
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1553
EP  - 1614
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - We present a new model of charitable giving where individuals regard out-of-pocket donations and the matches they induce as different. We show that match-price elasticities combine conventional price effects with the strength of warm glow, so that a match-price elasticity alone is insufficient to characterize preferences for giving. Match- and rebate-price elasticities will be different, but together they lead to new tests of underlying giving preferences. We estimate, for the first time, a match-price elasticity in a high-stakes setting together with a rebate elasticity induced by tax policy. The estimates reject extant models of giving but are consistent with the new theory.
AB  - We present a new model of charitable giving where individuals regard out-of-pocket donations and the matches they induce as different. We show that match-price elasticities combine conventional price effects with the strength of warm glow, so that a match-price elasticity alone is insufficient to characterize preferences for giving. Match- and rebate-price elasticities will be different, but together they lead to new tests of underlying giving preferences. We estimate, for the first time, a match-price elasticity in a high-stakes setting together with a rebate elasticity induced by tax policy. The estimates reject extant models of giving but are consistent with the new theory.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713190
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713190
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Exposure to Grocery Prices and Inflation Expectations
AU  - D’Acunto, Francesco
AU  - Malmendier, Ulrike
AU  - Ospina, Juan
AU  - Weber, Michael
Y1  - 2020/12/23
PY  - 2020
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713192
DO  - 10.1086/713192
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1615
EP  - 1639
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - Consumers rely on the price changes of goods in their grocery bundles when forming expectations about aggregate inflation. We use micro data that uniquely match individual expectations, detailed information about consumption bundles, and item-level prices. The weights consumers assign to price changes depend on the frequency of purchase, rather than expenditure share, and positive price changes loom larger than negative price changes. Prices of goods offered in the same store but not purchased do not affect inflation expectations, nor do other dimensions. Our results provide empirical guidance for models of expectations formation with heterogeneous consumers.
AB  - Consumers rely on the price changes of goods in their grocery bundles when forming expectations about aggregate inflation. We use micro data that uniquely match individual expectations, detailed information about consumption bundles, and item-level prices. The weights consumers assign to price changes depend on the frequency of purchase, rather than expenditure share, and positive price changes loom larger than negative price changes. Prices of goods offered in the same store but not purchased do not affect inflation expectations, nor do other dimensions. Our results provide empirical guidance for models of expectations formation with heterogeneous consumers.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713192
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713192
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

TY  - JOUR
T1  - Optimal Fiscal Policy without Commitment: Revisiting Lucas-Stokey
AU  - Debortoli, Davide
AU  - Nunes, Ricardo
AU  - Yared, Pierre
Y1  - 2021/01/11
PY  - 2021
DA  - 2021/05/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/713191
DO  - 10.1086/713191
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1640
EP  - 1665
VL  - 129
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - According to the Lucas-Stokey result, a government can structure its debt maturity to guarantee commitment to optimal fiscal policy by future governments. In this paper, we overturn this conclusion, showing that it does not generally hold in the same model and under the same definition of time consistency as in Lucas-Stokey. Our argument rests on the existence of an overlooked commitment problem that cannot be remedied with debt maturity: a government in the future will not necessarily tax above the peak of the Laffer curve, even if it is ex ante optimal to do so.
AB  - According to the Lucas-Stokey result, a government can structure its debt maturity to guarantee commitment to optimal fiscal policy by future governments. In this paper, we overturn this conclusion, showing that it does not generally hold in the same model and under the same definition of time consistency as in Lucas-Stokey. Our argument rests on the existence of an overlooked commitment problem that cannot be remedied with debt maturity: a government in the future will not necessarily tax above the peak of the Laffer curve, even if it is ex ante optimal to do so.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/713191
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/713191
Y2  - 2024/03/20
ER  - 

